<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Nov. 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Zebra Mussel Infestation of Great Lakes Could Be Costly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zebra mussels accidentally imported to
the <ORGANIZATION>Great Lakes</ORGANIZATION> in the <DATE>last four years</DATE> are threatening commercial
and sport fishing and forcing cities and industries into costly
measures to protect water supplies.
   The 2-inch-long mollusk, first dropped off an ocean-going
freighter in <LOCATION>Lake St. Clair</LOCATION> outside <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION>, has spread through
<LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION> and a colony was found in <LOCATION>Lake Michigan</LOCATION> near <LOCATION>Green Bay</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Wis.</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Michael Donahue</PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION>Great Lakes
Commission</ORGANIZATION>, headquartered in <LOCATION>Ann Arbor</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mich</LOCATION>.
   Intake pipes for industrial plants and municipal water systems
are among favorite breeding grounds for the greenish-striped
mussel. Monroe, <LOCATION>Mich.</LOCATION>, just south of <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION>, is designing a system
to bathe the mouth of its intake system with ozone-infused water in
hopes of killing the mussels' larvae, but there is very little that
apparently can be done to stem the surge of the mussels.
   Cleveland is also facing heavy bills to rid itself of an
infestation, and <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION> has been forced to partially close its
water plant.
   ``I will guarantee you that it may be <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Cleveland</LOCATION>'s
problem today, but it is going to be <PERSON>Gary</PERSON>'s and <LOCATION>Michigan City</LOCATION>'s
problem in the near future,'' <PERSON>Donahue</PERSON> said. ``There's just no way
to stop it.''
   In addition, the mussels feed voraciously on algae that other
fish and mollusks need, and could devastate <LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION>'s walleye
pike _ one of the lake's most important commercial fish, by
covering spawning grounds, said <PERSON>Jon Stanley</PERSON>, of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Fish and
<ORGANIZATION>Wildlife Service</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Ann Arbor</LOCATION>.
   ``Those actions in <LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION>, we expect, will reduce the walleye
population by about half,'' <ORGANIZATION>Stanley</ORGANIZATION> said. A ``good portion'' of the
estimated <MONEY>$600 million</MONEY> a year in <LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION> fisheries comes from
walleye.
   Beaches also could become fouled by the sharp-edged mussel
shells, <ORGANIZATION>Stanley</ORGANIZATION> said. ``You can notice the difference on some
beaches already. They used to be nice soft sand, but now they
crunch underfoot as you walk.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Researchers Use Dogs to Test Radon Exposure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zebra mussels accidentally imported to
the <ORGANIZATION>Great Lakes</ORGANIZATION> in the <DATE>last four years</DATE> are threatening commercial
and sport fishing and forcing cities and industries into costly
measures to protect water supplies.
   The 2-inch-long mollusk, first dropped off an ocean-going
freighter in <LOCATION>Lake St. Clair</LOCATION> outside <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION>, has spread through
<LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION> and a colony was found in <LOCATION>Lake Michigan</LOCATION> near <LOCATION>Green Bay</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Wis.</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Michael Donahue</PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION>Great Lakes
Commission</ORGANIZATION>, headquartered in <LOCATION>Ann Arbor</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mich</LOCATION>.
   Intake pipes for industrial plants and municipal water systems
are among favorite breeding grounds for the greenish-striped
mussel. Monroe, <LOCATION>Mich.</LOCATION>, just south of <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION>, is designing a system
to bathe the mouth of its intake system with ozone-infused water in
hopes of killing the mussels' larvae, but there is very little that
apparently can be done to stem the surge of the mussels.
   Cleveland is also facing heavy bills to rid itself of an
infestation, and <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION> has been forced to partially close its
water plant.
   ``I will guarantee you that it may be <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Cleveland</LOCATION>'s
problem today, but it is going to be <PERSON>Gary</PERSON>'s and <LOCATION>Michigan City</LOCATION>'s
problem in the near future,'' <PERSON>Donahue</PERSON> said. ``There's just no way
to stop it.''
   In addition, the mussels feed voraciously on algae that other
fish and mollusks need, and could devastate <LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION>'s walleye
pike _ one of the lake's most important commercial fish, by
covering spawning grounds, said <PERSON>Jon Stanley</PERSON>, of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Fish and
<ORGANIZATION>Wildlife Service</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Ann Arbor</LOCATION>.
   ``Those actions in <LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION>, we expect, will reduce the walleye
population by about half,'' <ORGANIZATION>Stanley</ORGANIZATION> said. A ``good portion'' of the
estimated <MONEY>$600 million</MONEY> a year in <LOCATION>Lake Erie</LOCATION> fisheries comes from
walleye.
   Beaches also could become fouled by the sharp-edged mussel
shells, <ORGANIZATION>Stanley</ORGANIZATION> said. ``You can notice the difference on some
beaches already. They used to be nice soft sand, but now they
crunch underfoot as you walk.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 27</NOTE>
