<HEAD>Senate Adds $20 Million to Farm Bill to Stop Zebra Mussel Spread</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> has approved a <MONEY>$20 million</MONEY> research
and prevention program to keep zebra mussels from invading farm
irrigation systems.
   The striped mollusk, which is not native to <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION>, has
caused problems at water and power plants throughout the Great
Lakes. They attach to water intake pipes and clog them.
   An amendment authorizing the <MONEY>$20 million</MONEY> over five years was
added to the <DATE>1990</DATE> farm bill by <PERSON>Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-N.Y.</LOCATION>
   ``Unlike other infestations, this one is irreversible,''
<PERSON>Moynihan</PERSON> said in a statement <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. ``The zebra mussel is here
to stay ... Within 20 years' time it will have spread through the
entire surface water system of <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION>.''
   The amendment, which the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> passed <DATE>late Wednesday</DATE>, directs
the <ORGANIZATION>Department of Agriculture</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Army Corps of Engineers</ORGANIZATION>
to develop a program of research, prevention and design criteria
for irrigation systems with an emphasis on keeping the mussels out.
   On <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, scientists expressed surprise that the tiny
mollusks are spreading through the <ORGANIZATION>Erie Canal</ORGANIZATION> system from <LOCATION>Buffalo</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>, and now threaten <LOCATION>Rochester</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION> and the Finger Lakes region.
   ``Frankly, I did not think their advance would be this fast,''
said <PERSON>Cameron Lange</PERSON>, a biologist studying the mussels' movement for
a consortium of power companies.
   ``I thought we might find a few at <LOCATION>Lockport</LOCATION> during our <DATE>late July</DATE>
sample but I did not think they'd reach Rochester by now.''
   Rochester is about 60 miles east of <LOCATION>Lockport</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>
   In <DATE>May</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works</ORGANIZATION>
authorized <MONEY>$37.5 million</MONEY> in grants and research funding for control
of the mussel. The provision is part of the pending Water Resources
Development Act of <DATE>1990</DATE>.
</TEXT>
